# Working memory protocol (claude-task-templates)

This machine has the `claude-task-templates` system installed. A `UserPromptSubmit`
hook injects task context on every prompt when an active task exists in the current
repo's `.claude-task/`. Treat that injected block as authoritative ‚Äî it tells you
exactly which task you're on and what to do next.

## On first prompt of a session, when injected context shows an active task

Before doing anything else, perform a **takeover**:

1. Read `.claude-task/<slug>/STATUS.md` (full file, not just the injected excerpt).
2. Read `.claude-task/<slug>/BRIEF.md`.
3. Read `.claude-task/<slug>/NEXT.md`.
4. Skim the newest 5‚Äì10 entries of `.claude-task/<slug>/DECISIONS.md`.
5. Update STATUS.md frontmatter: set `owner` to your model name, set `session_id`
   to the current Claude session UUID if known (else leave it), bump `updated`
   to the current UTC timestamp.

Only open `LOG.md` if STATUS/BRIEF/NEXT/DECISIONS leave you confused.

After the takeover, proceed with the user's prompt. The takeover should take under
five minutes and runs implicitly ‚Äî don't narrate it unless the user asks.

## During work ‚Äî checkpoint at every natural pause

A natural pause is: finishing a phase, hitting a blocker, switching focus, before
running a long-running task, or when you sense you've accumulated meaningful state
since the last checkpoint. Don't wait for the user to ask.

A checkpoint is:

1. Rewrite the "Where we are" paragraph in `STATUS.md` (‚â§80 words) and bump
   `updated`. Update `status`, `blockers_open`, `next_action_owner` if they changed.
2. Overwrite `NEXT.md` with the literal next 1‚Äì3 things to do ‚Äî specific enough
   that an arriving agent can start without thinking. Include file paths, commands,
   commit hashes.
3. Append an entry to `LOG.md` (newest at top): `## YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM ¬∑ headline`
   followed by 1‚Äì3 sentences citing commits/PRs/files.
4. If a new irreversible choice was made: append to `DECISIONS.md` with a Why-line.
5. If a new artifact was produced (commit, PR, file, URL): append to `ARTIFACTS.md`.

Target: ‚â§2 minutes per checkpoint. Cheaper than reconstructing context after a reset.

## When the user describes substantial new work and there is no active task

If the user describes a piece of work expected to span more than one session,
or that produces decisions worth preserving, **scaffold a task automatically**:

1. Pick a slug (lowercase-kebab from the title, ‚â§60 chars).
2. Run `claude-task-init <slug> --title "<title>"` (it's on `$PATH` from
   `~/claude-task-templates/bin/`). If `$PATH` doesn't have it, call by absolute
   path `~/claude-task-templates/bin/claude-task-init`.
3. Populate `BRIEF.md` from the conversation context (goal, scope, success
   criteria, constraints, source spec link if any).
4. Write the first `NEXT.md` with a concrete first step.
5. Set `STATUS.md` `status: in_progress` and bump `updated`.
6. Confirm to the user: "Scaffolded task `<slug>`. BRIEF and NEXT filled in.
   Starting on ‚Ä¶".

Skip this for trivial one-shot work (typo fixes, quick questions). The threshold
is "spans more than one session OR produces non-trivial decisions worth preserving."

## When status flips to done or abandoned

1. Final checkpoint (success-criteria check-off, last LOG entry).
2. `mv .claude-task/<slug> .claude-task/_archive/<slug>`
3. Truncate `.claude-task/ACTIVE` (or set it to the next task the user wants).

## When LOG.md exceeds 500 lines

Run a fold during the next checkpoint:

1. Identify the 200 oldest entries (bottom of file).
2. Write a `## Summarized through <date>` block at the top: 5‚Äì15 bullets, one per
   major arc, preserving commit hashes / PR numbers / key file paths.
3. Delete the 200 original entries that were folded.

## Never

- Edit `BRIEF.md` after init. Scope changes go in `DECISIONS.md` instead.
- Skip checkpoints to save time ‚Äî that's the failure mode this whole system exists
  to prevent.
- Create a task folder for trivial one-shot work.
- Store secrets in any of these files (plaintext on disk).
- Use the auto-memory system (`~/.claude/projects/.../memory/`) for per-task state.
  Per-task state belongs in `.claude-task/`. Auto-memory is for slow-moving facts.
